Data analysis of influences on health and economy by severe weather events

Synopsis

The goal of this analysis is to find the severe weather events which have the most damaging influence on public health and economy through the data from 1950~2011. For public health, the total injuries and fatalities were calculated for each severe weather event. And for economy, the crop damage and property damage were calculated for for each severe weather event. Figures were generated to illustrate the damaging effect for top 30 severe weather event. From the figures, we can conclude that tornados are the biggest cause for both fatalities and injuries. Flooding causes most property damage and overall economic damage, whereas drought causes most crop damage.

Introduction

Storms and other severe weather events can cause both public health and economic problems for communities and municipalities. Many severe events can result in fatalities, injuries, and property damage, and preventing such outcomes to the extent possible is a key concern.

This project involves exploring the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration’s (NOAA) storm database. This database tracks characteristics of major storms and weather events in the United States, including when and where they occur, as well as estimates of any fatalities, injuries, and property damage. The data can be download through link Storm Data [47Mb]

Analysis for economic problems caused by severe weather events

5.Create a function to find the corresponding value of symbol in CROPDMGEXP and PROPDMGEXP,e.g,return 10^3 for “K” or “k”,return 10^6 for “M” or “m”,return 10^9 for “B” or “b”, for other cases, return 1

symb<-data.frame(letter=c("k","K","m","M","b","B"),number=rep(c(10^3,10^6,10^9),each=2)) #symb is data frame to find represented value of the symbol
findsymb<-function(x){
  y<-symb[match(x,symb[[1]]),2]
  if(is.na(y))y<-1
y
}
fs<-Vectorize(findsymb) #vectorize the findsymbol function

6.Calculate the property damage and crop damage by multiplying the value in PROPDMG/CROPDMG and corresponding value indicated by PROPDMGEXP/CROPDMGEXP (through fs function)

datatb[,`:=`(PROPDMGn=PROPDMG*fs(PROPDMGEXP),CROPDMGn=CROPDMG*fs(CROPDMGEXP))]

7.Calculate total property damage or total crop damage for differen kinds of severe weather events

DT2<-datatb[,.(Property_damage=sum(PROPDMGn),Crop_damage=sum(CROPDMGn)),by=EVTYPE]

Result

Result for public health problems caused by severe weather events

Plot the top 30 severe weather events that affect public health

ggplot(DT1topn,aes(EVTYPE,Problems,fill=Type))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90,hjust=1))+xlab("Event Type")+ylab("Fatalities and injuries")+ggtitle("Figure1. Fatalities and injuries caused by\ntop 30 severe weather events")

Discussion and conclusion

Figure1 reveals that the severe weather event which caused most fatalities and injuries was tornado.

Result for economic problems caused by severe weather events

Plot the top 30 severe weather events that affect economy

ggplot(DT2topn,aes(EVTYPE,Damages,fill=Type))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90,hjust=1))+xlab("Event Type")+ylab("Damages (Dollars)")+ggtitle("Figure2. Property and Crop damage caused by\ntop 30 severe weather events")

Discussion and conclusion

Figure2 shows that the severe weather event which caused most economic damage was flooding. Flooding also caused the most of the property damage. But drought caused the most of the crop damage.
